<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1230,1675]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,559,1301,1327]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
The Guayana Highlands in southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1071,1191,1301,1327]" name="Venezuela" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(to be expected in adjacent 
<collectingCountry box="[262,359,1340,1366]" name="Guyana" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Guyana</collectingCountry>
) and the Andes in northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[766,895,1340,1366]" name="Venezuela" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[909,1033,1340,1366]" name="Colombia" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1151,1340,1366]" name="Ecuador" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1218,1278,1340,1366]" name="Peru" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Peru</collectingCountry>
. Is is locally common along humid forest edges, along roads, on landslides, and along streams at 
<quantity box="[1137,1302,1378,1404]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="m" value="2350.0" valueMax="3000.0" valueMin="1700.0">1700–3000 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,1230,1675]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,307,1417,1443]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Notes:—</emphasis>
Morphologically, this species is at the center of a complex of seven closely related species which include: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Sodiro" box="[255,449,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="blepharolepis">
<emphasis box="[255,449,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. blepharolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copeland" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Christ &amp; Rosenst." box="[464,614,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="buchtienii">
<emphasis box="[464,614,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. buchtienii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" box="[630,727,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jacha">
<emphasis box="[630,727,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. jacha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="J. Gonzales" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[743,865,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanosus">
<emphasis box="[743,865,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. lanosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1990" baseAuthorityName="Cav. ex Sw." box="[880,1045,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosus">
<emphasis box="[880,1045,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. tomentosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Copeland" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Kunze" box="[1112,1227,1456,1481]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="velatus">
<emphasis box="[1112,1227,1456,1481]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. velatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Traditionally all seven taxa have been considered to belong to a single, variable species (
<bibRefCitation author="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G." box="[1008,1264,1495,1521]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref34267" refString="Tryon, R. M. &amp; Stolze, R. G. (1989) Pteridophyta of Peru. Part II. 13. Pteridaceae - 15. Dennstaedtiaceae. Fieldiana Botany, n. s. 22: 1 - 122." type="book chapter" year="1989">Tryon &amp; Stolze 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ostergaard A. &amp; Ollgaard, E." pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="107 - 169" refId="ref33047" refString="Ostergaard A., Ollgaard, E. &amp; B. (2001) Gleicheniaceae. In Harling, G. &amp; Andersson, L. (eds.), Flora of Ecuador 66: 107 - 169." type="journal article" year="2001">Østergaard &amp; Øllgaard 2001</bibRefCitation>
). In their study of the genus in 
<collectingCountry box="[746,853,1533,1559]" name="Ecuador" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ostergaard A. &amp; Ollgaard, E." box="[868,1253,1533,1559]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="107 - 169" refId="ref33047" refString="Ostergaard A., Ollgaard, E. &amp; B. (2001) Gleicheniaceae. In Harling, G. &amp; Andersson, L. (eds.), Flora of Ecuador 66: 107 - 169." type="journal article" year="2001">Østergaard &amp; Øllgaard (2001)</bibRefCitation>
recognized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ching" authorityYear="1940" baseAuthorityName="Sodiro" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="blepharolepis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">S. blepharolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a distinct species. A closer examination of the morphological variability of the complex over its entire geographical distribution has convinced us that there are seven distinct entities, which are treated here at the species level.
</paragraph>
